    "[purpose]: The site is informative and focused on technical community building and education. Navigation is straightforward with no significant blockers encountered.",
    "[nav]: The site is primarily informational and community-driven, lacking commerce or complex authentication for general browsing. Navigation is flat and accessible via a clear header and homepage hero blocks.",
    "[auth]: The website https://hckr.cc redirects to https://www.nushackers.org, which is a static informational site for a student organization. Thorough scouting of the homepage, sub-sites (Hack&Roll), community pages, and common authentication paths (e.g., /login, /admin, /signup) revealed no native sign-in, sign-up, or account-related entry points. Registration for events like Hack&Roll is mentioned in FAQs but typically occurs through external platforms like Devpost or Google Forms, and is currently closed. No internal member portal or dashboard was found.",
    "[commerce]: The website hckr.cc redirects to nushackers.org, which is the official site for the NUS Hackers student community. The site primarily serves as an informational portal for their workshops (Hackerschool), hackathons (Hack&Roll), and community events (Friday Hacks). All events are described as free and open to the public, and no product listings, shopping carts, or checkout flows were identified during the scout. The site does not contain commercial elements.",
    "[support]: Privacy Policy, Terms of Service, Security, and Status pages were not found in the main IA. The site appears to be for a student organization (NUS Hackers), and legal/trust information is primarily contained within the 'Event code of conduct' page."
